---
import CalculatorLayout from '../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import HourlyPaycheckCalculator from '../components/calculators/HourlyPaycheckCalculator';
import { TAX_YEAR } from '../lib/constants';

const title = `$X/Hour to Annual Salary: ${TAX_YEAR} Hourly Pay Calculator`;
const description = `Convert your hourly wage to annual salary and see take-home pay after taxes. Free ${TAX_YEAR} hourly paycheck calculator with federal, state, and FICA breakdowns.`;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How do I convert my hourly rate to an annual salary?',
    answer: `Multiply your hourly rate by the number of hours you work per week, then multiply by 52 weeks. For example, $25/hour × 40 hours × 52 weeks = $52,000 per year. This is your gross annual salary before taxes. Your actual take-home pay will be lower after federal, state, and FICA taxes.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'How much is $15 an hour annually after taxes?',
    answer: `At $15/hour working 40 hours per week, your gross annual salary is $31,200. After federal income tax, FICA (7.65%), and state taxes, a Single filer in a no-income-tax state would take home approximately $27,200-$27,800 per year, or about $1,045-$1,070 per bi-weekly paycheck. State income tax can reduce this further.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Does this calculator account for overtime pay?',
    answer: `This calculator estimates take-home pay based on your regular hourly rate and standard work hours. For overtime calculations (time and a half for hours over 40/week), use our <a href="/overtime-pay-calculator/" class="text-navy-600 underline dark:text-navy-400">Overtime Pay Calculator</a>. Federal law requires 1.5× pay for non-exempt employees working over 40 hours per week.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'How many hours per year is full-time?',
    answer: `Full-time is typically 2,080 hours per year (40 hours/week × 52 weeks). However, actual work hours vary: some jobs are 37.5 hours/week (1,950/year), and when you account for paid holidays (typically 10 days) and vacation (average 10-15 days), actual hours worked may be 1,800-1,960.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between hourly and salaried pay?',
    answer: `Hourly workers are paid for each hour worked and are usually eligible for overtime (1.5× pay after 40 hours/week). Salaried workers receive a fixed amount per pay period regardless of hours. Under FLSA rules, salaried employees earning under $58,656/year in ${TAX_YEAR} may still qualify for overtime. Tax withholding works the same for both.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'How much is $20 an hour bi-weekly after taxes?',
    answer: `At $20/hour (40 hrs/week), your gross bi-weekly paycheck is $1,600 ($41,600/year). After federal income tax, FICA, and state tax, a Single filer in a no-tax state takes home roughly $1,330-$1,370 bi-weekly. In a state with income tax, expect $1,260-$1,340 depending on the rate.`,
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  { title: 'Paycheck Calculator', href: '/', desc: 'General paycheck calculator' },
  { title: 'Salary Calculator', href: '/salary-calculator/', desc: 'Annual salary breakdown' },
  { title: 'Overtime Pay Calculator', href: '/overtime-pay-calculator/', desc: 'Calculate OT after taxes' },
  { title: 'Tip Tax Calculator', href: '/tip-tax-calculator/', desc: 'Tipped employee take-home' },
  { title: 'Income Tax Calculator', href: '/income-tax-calculator/', desc: 'Federal + state tax estimate' },
];

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebApplication',
  name: `Hourly Paycheck Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`,
  description,
  url: 'https://truetakehomepay.com/hourly-paycheck-calculator',
  applicationCategory: 'FinanceApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Any',
  offers: {
    '@type': 'Offer',
    price: '0',
    priceCurrency: 'USD',
  },
  inLanguage: 'en-US',
};
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  h1={`Hourly Paycheck Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`}
  intro={`Convert your hourly wage to annual, monthly, or bi-weekly take-home pay. Enter your hourly rate and hours worked to see your net pay after federal and state taxes, FICA, and deductions.`}
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
  schema={schema}
  sources={`IRS Rev. Proc. 2025-11 (${TAX_YEAR} federal tax brackets), U.S. Department of Labor (FLSA overtime rules), SSA.gov (Social Security wage base). Last updated for tax year ${TAX_YEAR}.`}
>
  <HourlyPaycheckCalculator client:load />
  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="border-t border-slate-200 px-4 py-16 dark:border-slate-800 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
        <h2 id="hourly-work-in-america">Hourly Work in America: The Landscape for Wage Earners</h2>
        <p>More than 78 million American workers, roughly 55% of the wage and salary workforce, are paid on an hourly basis according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. Hourly employment spans an enormous range of occupations, from entry-level retail and food service positions to highly skilled trades like electricians, plumbers, and registered nurses who can earn $40 to $60 or more per hour. The common thread among all hourly workers is that compensation is directly tied to time worked, which creates a different financial planning dynamic compared to salaried positions.</p>
        <p>The federal minimum wage has been $7.25 per hour since 2009, making it the longest period without an increase since the minimum wage was established in 1938. However, the federal floor tells only part of the story. As of 2025, 30 states plus the District of Columbia have set their own minimum wages above the federal level. Washington state and the District of Columbia lead with minimums above $17 per hour, while California's minimum is $16.50 statewide and higher in many cities. Some cities have enacted their own minimums that exceed the state level, such as Seattle at over $19 per hour for large employers. If you are paid at or near the minimum wage, your state and city rates determine your actual floor. Use the calculator above to see exactly how your hourly wage translates to take-home pay in your specific state.</p>
        <p>Hourly workers face a unique challenge that salaried employees do not: income variability. Schedules can fluctuate week to week based on employer staffing needs, seasonal demand, and business conditions. A retail worker might get 35 hours one week and 22 the next. This variability makes budgeting difficult because take-home pay is essentially unpredictable. Financial advisors who specialize in working with hourly earners recommend building budgets around the minimum expected hours rather than the maximum, and treating any additional hours as surplus to be directed toward savings or debt repayment.</p>

        <h2 id="converting-hourly-to-annual">How to Convert Your Hourly Wage to an Annual Salary</h2>
        <p>Converting an hourly rate to an annual salary is essential for comparing job offers, qualifying for loans, and understanding your earning power in a broader context. The standard conversion formula multiplies your hourly rate by the number of hours worked per week and then by 52 weeks. At 40 hours per week, the math produces a clean result: $20 per hour equals $41,600 per year, $25 per hour equals $52,000, and $30 per hour equals $62,400.</p>
        <p>However, the standard calculation assumes you work every week of the year, which is rarely the case for hourly workers. If your employer does not offer paid time off, every day you miss work is a day without pay. Taking two weeks of unpaid vacation reduces your actual annual earnings by approximately 3.8%. An hourly worker earning $22 per hour who takes two weeks unpaid receives $43,120 instead of the theoretical $45,760. Sick days, personal days, and holidays without pay further reduce actual earnings. When comparing an hourly position to a salaried offer, account for paid time off as part of the total compensation package. A salaried position at $44,000 with three weeks of paid vacation may be more valuable than an hourly position at $22 per hour with no PTO, despite the hourly rate implying a higher annual equivalent.</p>
        <p>Part-time hourly workers need to adjust the formula for their actual hours. Someone working 25 hours per week at $18 per hour earns a gross annual income of $23,400, not the $37,440 that the 40-hour calculation would suggest. If you are evaluating whether part-time work makes financial sense, consider not only the gross income but also the impact on benefits eligibility. Many employers only offer health insurance, retirement plans, and other benefits to employees who work 30 or more hours per week. Losing access to employer-sponsored health insurance could cost $300 to $600 per month on the individual marketplace, dramatically reducing the net value of part-time earnings. Our <a href="/salary-calculator/">salary calculator</a> can help you model the annual take-home pay equivalent of different hourly and salaried arrangements.</p>

        <h2 id="hourly-wages-and-overtime">The Reality of Hourly Wages and Overtime</h2>
        <p>Overtime is where hourly work can become significantly more lucrative than salaried employment. Under the Fair Labor Standards Act, non-exempt hourly employees must receive at least 1.5 times their regular hourly rate for every hour worked beyond 40 in a single workweek. Some states have even more generous overtime provisions. California, for example, requires overtime pay after 8 hours in a single day, not just after 40 hours in a week. This means a California worker who puts in four 12-hour days and takes Fridays off earns 16 hours of overtime pay even though total weekly hours are only 48, well above the 8 hours of overtime they would earn under federal rules alone.</p>
        <p>The financial impact of consistent overtime is substantial. An employee earning $24 per hour who works 50 hours every week receives $960 for the first 40 hours and $360 for the 10 overtime hours at $36 per hour, bringing the weekly gross to $1,320. Over 52 weeks, this totals $68,640, which is $18,720 more than the $49,920 base salary at 40 hours. That 37.5% increase in gross pay comes with a proportional increase in taxes, though the effective tax rate on the overtime portion may be higher because those dollars sit in a higher marginal bracket. The <a href="/overtime-pay-calculator/">overtime pay calculator</a> on this site can show you exactly how overtime affects your after-tax income.</p>
        <p>It is important to understand that overtime pay is not optional for employers. The FLSA requires it, and violations carry significant penalties. Some employers attempt to avoid overtime obligations by misclassifying workers as exempt salaried employees, pressuring workers to clock out and continue working, or averaging hours across two-week periods instead of calculating overtime weekly. All of these practices are illegal under federal law. If you suspect your employer is not paying proper overtime, the Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division investigates complaints, and workers can recover back wages plus liquidated damages equal to the unpaid amount.</p>

        <h2 id="part-time-vs-full-time">Part-Time Versus Full-Time Hourly Considerations</h2>
        <p>The distinction between part-time and full-time hourly employment extends far beyond the number of hours worked. The Affordable Care Act defines full-time as 30 or more hours per week for the purpose of employer-provided health insurance, meaning employers with 50 or more full-time equivalent employees must offer affordable health coverage to workers averaging 30 or more hours. This threshold has created a significant dividing line in the hourly labor market, with some employers deliberately capping part-time schedules at 29 hours to avoid triggering the insurance requirement.</p>
        <p>For workers, the 30-hour threshold represents a financial cliff. Crossing from 29 to 30 hours may not significantly increase gross pay, since it adds only one additional hour of wages per week, but it could open access to employer-sponsored health insurance worth $6,000 to $8,000 annually. If you are a part-time hourly worker hovering near 30 hours, understanding whether your employer tracks hours for ACA purposes and whether benefits would be offered can have a profound impact on your total compensation and financial security.</p>
        <p>Part-time work serves a valuable role for many Americans, including students, parents with young children, semi-retired individuals, and people balancing multiple jobs. About 26 million Americans work part-time by choice, according to the BLS. For these workers, the key financial planning challenge is managing variable income and securing benefits independently. Those without employer-sponsored insurance can access coverage through the ACA marketplace, where subsidies are available for households earning up to 400% of the federal poverty level. A single person earning $25,000 from part-time work might qualify for substantial premium subsidies that bring marketplace coverage costs down to $100 to $200 per month.</p>
        <p>Workers who hold multiple part-time jobs face additional complexity in managing their tax withholding. Each employer withholds as if their job is the worker's only source of income, which means the combined withholding may fall short of the actual tax liability because each job calculates withholding starting from the bottom of the tax brackets. A worker with two part-time jobs each paying $20,000 may find that each employer withholds as if the worker earns only $20,000, applying the lowest brackets. In reality, the combined $40,000 income places some dollars in a higher bracket, resulting in a tax bill at filing time. Submitting a W-4 with additional withholding on one or both jobs, or making estimated tax payments, can prevent this shortfall.</p>

        <h2 id="benefits-for-hourly-workers">How Benefits Affect Hourly Workers Differently</h2>
        <p>The benefits gap between hourly and salaried workers is one of the most significant but least discussed factors in American compensation. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics Employee Benefits Survey, only 51% of private-sector workers in the lowest wage quartile have access to employer-sponsored health insurance, compared to 90% of workers in the highest wage quartile. Similarly, only 46% of the lowest-paid workers have access to a retirement plan at work, versus 86% of the highest-paid workers.</p>
        <p>This benefits gap has enormous long-term financial consequences. An hourly worker without a 401(k) misses out on employer matching contributions, tax-deferred growth, and the behavioral nudge of automatic payroll deductions. Over a 30-year career, a worker who receives a 3% employer match on a $40,000 salary accumulates roughly $113,000 in matching contributions alone (assuming 7% annual returns), not counting their own contributions. Without access to a workplace plan, the same worker would need to proactively open an IRA and contribute consistently, something that research shows is far less common than participating in an employer-offered plan. The <a href="/roth-ira-calculator/">Roth IRA calculator</a> can help hourly workers without employer plans model the growth of independent retirement savings.</p>
        <p>Paid time off is another area where hourly workers face significant disadvantages. The United States is the only advanced economy that does not mandate paid vacation or sick leave at the federal level. While many states and cities have enacted their own paid sick leave laws, paid vacation remains entirely at the employer's discretion. The BLS reports that workers in the lowest wage category receive an average of 8 paid vacation days per year, compared to 15 days for the highest-paid workers. Some hourly positions offer no paid time off at all, meaning every day away from work directly reduces income.</p>
        <p>For hourly workers evaluating job opportunities, calculating the total value of benefits is just as important as comparing hourly rates. A job paying $19 per hour with employer-sponsored health insurance, a 3% 401(k) match, and 10 days of paid vacation is likely worth more than a job paying $22 per hour with no benefits. The health insurance alone could be worth $4 to $5 per hour in equivalent compensation, and the retirement match adds another $0.50 to $1.00 per hour. Viewed this way, the $19 per hour position with benefits may actually deliver $24 to $25 per hour in total compensation, making it the clearly superior offer.</p>
        <p>Understanding your hourly wage in the context of taxes, overtime potential, benefits access, and annual earnings is essential for making sound financial decisions. Whether you are negotiating for more hours, comparing job offers, or planning a transition to salaried work, this calculator gives you the foundation to evaluate your options with clarity. Explore our <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator/">take-home pay calculator</a> and <a href="/income-tax-calculator/">income tax calculator</a> for additional perspectives on how your earnings translate into real spending power.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
